</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>f \colon  A \to  B</fr:tex> be a <fr:link
href="erct-000Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000Y">section</fr:link> of some <fr:tex>r \colon  B \to  A</fr:tex>; the type of <fr:link
href="erct-000Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000Y">sections</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is, then, a <fr:link
href="erct-001I.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001I">proposition</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1354</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>31</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>erct-002Q</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>Using the <fr:link
href="erct-0015.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-0015">univalence principle for dependent function spaces</fr:link>, we can see that the type of <fr:link
href="erct-000Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000Y">sections</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f \colon  A \to  B</fr:tex> is a <fr:link
href="erct-0025.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-0025">retract</fr:link> of the <fr:link
href="erct-001Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001Q">fiber</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f \circ  -</fr:tex> at <fr:tex>1_{ B }</fr:tex>, using the <fr:link
href="erct-0023.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-0023">univalence principle for sections</fr:link>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>To show that the type of <fr:link
href="erct-000Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000Y">sections</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is a <fr:link
href="erct-001I.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001I">proposition</fr:link>, we may assume beforehand that we have such a <fr:link
href="erct-000Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000Y">section</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex>; therefore, because we have assumed a <fr:link
href="erct-000Y.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000Y">retraction</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> already, we know that <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="erct-000U.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-000U">biinvertible</fr:link> and <fr:link
href="erct-002N.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-002N">therefore</fr:link> that <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="erct-001T.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001T">contractible</fr:link>. By <fr:ref
addr="erct-0026"
href="erct-0026.xml"
taxon="Lemma"></fr:ref>, it suffices to show that the <fr:link
href="erct-001Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001Q">fiber</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f \circ  -</fr:tex> at <fr:tex>1_{ B }</fr:tex> is a <fr:link
href="erct-001I.xml"
type="local"
addr="erct-001I">proposition</fr:link>, which follows via <fr:ref
addr="erct-001K"
href="erct-001K.xml"
taxon="Lemma"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="erct-002O"
href="erct-002O.xml"
taxon="Lemma"></fr:ref>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
